EPIZOOTIC HEMORRHAGIC DISEASE, BOVINE - ISRAEL (02): (HAZAFON, JERUSALEM) CONFIRMED, OIE
****************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 14 Oct 2015
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information 2015; 28(42) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=18859

Epizootic haemorrhagic disease, Israel
--------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 14 Oct 2015 from Dr Nadav Galon, Director, Veterinary Services and Animal Health, Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development, Bet Dagan, Israel

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 16 Sep 2015
Date of confirmation of the event: 7 Oct 2015
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 2006
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: epizootic haemorrhagic disease virus
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (basic), laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks (3)
Outbreak 1 (Sha'Ar Hagolan): Sha'Ar Hagolan, Kineret, Hazafon [Northern district]
Date of start of the outbreak: 16 Sep 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle/ 350 / 20 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: Dairy cows showing drop in milk production, swollen feet and limping.

Outbreak 2 (Almog): Almog, Jericho, Yerushalayim [Jerusalem]
Date of start of the outbreak: 27 Sep 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle/ 500 / 50 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: dairy cows showing drop in milk production, limping, and red mucosa.

Outbreak 3 (Qalya): Qalya, Jericho, Yerushalayim [Jerusalem]
Date of start of the outbreak: 28 Sep 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle/ 550 / 100 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: slight signs as drop in milk production, reduced rumination, and limping.

Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 3
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle/ 1400 / 170 / 0 / 0 / 0
Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]:
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Cattle / 12.14 / 0 / 0 / 0
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: vectors

Control measures
Measures applied: control of vectors; no vaccination; treatment of affected animals (supportive therapy)
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type:
Kimron Veterinary Institute, Virology Division (National laboratory)
Species / Test / Test date / Result
Cattle/ antibody detection ELISA/ 5 Oct 2015/ Positive
Cattle/ polymerase chain/ 7 Oct 2015/ Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreaks can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This immediate notification confirms the suspicion of epizootic hemorrhagic disease (EHD) published in ProMED-mail, archive number 20151010.3706490. As Mod AS's mentions in this posting, EHD has also been diagnosed recently in Tunisia. On 12 Oct 2015, Tunisia sent to the OIE a final report closing their EHD event. However, the report did not indicate what serotype was identified. See report at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?reportid=18843. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3718085,32001.]
